description.narrative: By 2022, national systems for harmonized procurement, logistics and supply chain management are strengthened for equitable and quality Maternal, Neonatal, and Child Health (MNCH), immunization, nutrition and HIV service delivery, which contributes to Child Health, Hiv Prevention, Immunization, Maternal And Newborn Health, Operations Support To Programme Delivery, Prevention Of Stunting And Other Forms Of Malnutrition, Treatment Of Severe Acute Malnutrition. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, more children under 5 and women of reproductive age equitably access and utilize evidence-based health, HIV & nutrition interventions, including adoption of key behaviours, especially among vulnerable populations in most deprived states/regions, conflict-affected and peri-urban areas (Goal Area 1 UNICEF Strategic Framework 2018-2021)

description.narrative: Largest impact seen from COVID-19 pandemic on supply chain is interruption in global transport on essential commodities for routine services including vaccines and cold chain equipment, as they are re-prioritized to COVID-19 response commodities such as PPE and test kits. After suspension in April and May, Ministry of Health and Sports successfully resumed immunization services in June, by customizing approaches where immunization services are provided with infection prevention and control against COVID-19. The country had adequate vaccines stock and activities for strengthening supply chain management were soon accelerated in collaboration with Ministry of Health and Sports and WHO. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:30/07/2020
